title: For Sale:  Don't overpay... check these links to save some $$$
postcontent:
Here's some links to help save you some $$$.  I am a FFL03 holder (C&R) so I can get quite a few guns shipped direct to me, but I also have my FFL dealer listed.  I can't stand the price gouging going on here (and the local dealers and the show) so I had to post...
FFL’s
Fish Safari - $20 transfers - http://www.fishsafari.com/ffl.html
The Armory - $35 transfers, paperwork must be completed first - http://www.the-armory.com/
Deals
www.slickguns.com/today  That’s the best site for up to the minute pricing.
www.gunbot.net – Ammo price crawler. 
Dealers 
Classic Firearms – C&R and new guns, ammo, accessories.  Reasonable prices and great service.
http://www.classicfirearms.com/
J&G Sales - C&R and new guns, ammo, accessories.  Shipping high but huge stock.
			http://www.jgsales.com/
Widener’s –  C&R and new guns, ammo, accessories, and reloading supplies. 
			http://www.wideners.com/index.cfm
Centerfire Systems –  C&R and new guns, ammo, accessories.  Good resource for magazines.
			http://centerfiresystems.com/
KY Gun Co – New guns.  Great selection and prices.
			http://www.kygunco.com/
Bud’s Guns –   New and C&R guns.  Charges 3% for CC, sometimes a “membership” fee.  Generally free shipping.
			http://www.budsgunshop.com/catalog/index.php
AIM Surplus – C&R and new guns, ammo, accessories.  Reasonable shipping.  Good for ammo and mags.
			http://www.aimsurplus.com/
Sovereign Guns – C&R and new.  Some ammo and accessories.  Shipping reasonable.  They get some strange stuff.
			http://www.sovereignguns.com/
Price Research-
New guns – KY Gun co and Buds Guns.  I use Gun Broker, but only the average SOLD price.  
Ammo – If I can’t find it at AIM or Classic, I go to the Armory to research. 
C&R – Century International Arms (www.centuryarms.biz) .  Must be a dealer (or C&R) and request an account.  Best prices for available items.  Shipping super cheap as long as your order is over $75.

Good luck and don't overpay.  The AWB is dead.  Prices are coming down (AK's and AR's were around $800 at the show and online) and ammo is available.

title: For Sale:  French Lebel Rifle - Model 1907/15 - Made in 1927 - Beautiful Condition
postcontent:
For Sale today is a French Model 1907/15 Lebel rifle that has hung on my office wall for 20 years. Unfortunately I work for a Fortune 500 company who has recently requested that I remove it due to the anti-gun sentiments we all face these days. So since I'm just a few short years from retiring (with a rather nice pension) - I decided to comply. My wife also told me that it didn't fit our decor so no chance of hanging it over the fireplace at home... Ha!

The quick story on this rifle is that I lived next to an older retired gentleman many years ago whose full time retirement passion was collecting and refinishing/restoring old military firearms. He only worked on older rifles that dated from WWII or before.

Every few years he'd make a road trip in his van, and he'd come back with a big pile of rifles. He told me he would stop by some of the big importers who in those days let him pick through their piles of rifles that were too beat up to sell easily. Of course that was what he was looking for and he picked the rifles that were a physically unattractive, but that were in good working shape mechanically. He would sometimes spend weeks working on a single rifle to make it beautiful, and I can tell you that no one who came to my office for the first time ever went more than 5 minutes without asking about this beautiful old rifle. So it's an incredible conversation piece.

Additionally he told me that this rifle would be perfectly safe to fire and even gave me (4) clips of ammo which is 8mm Lebel. These cartridges and clips go along with the rifle as does the original French " needle style" bayonet. The bayonet is in nice shape and has a brass handle, but it's not as nice as the rifle. I looked on eBay recently and similar bayonets are listed for $125+ by themselves.

 I never fired this rifle so I must say that you need to get your gunsmith to take a look at it before firing. Even though there isn't a speck of rust or corrosion on it anywhere - be safe and get an expert's opinion.

I did take a look through the barrel and rifling appears very good with no rust or pitting, and there is even some shine to my older eyes.

Finally I had a difficult time trying to take good pictures of this rifle with the camera I have. So the three pictures allowed by Armslist really don't capture the true beauty of this rifle. I'd be more than happy to arrange a time for a SERIOUS buyer to take a closer look.

Price for the rifle, clips & ammo, and the bayonet is $575. The rifle was made in 1927 so it's not a true antique in the eyes of the law. Therefore you must be a Florida resident and at least 21 to buy.

Thanks for looking

 Gun Review: Raven MP-25 Semi-automatic pistol
"Raven MP-25 has a tumultuous history and remains a controversial piece of the American firearms scene. It was designed by the famous George Jennings, and is the original, quintessential, “Saturday night special.” Reviled by journalists and anti-crime activists for its extreme popularity with criminals, this weapon suffered a smear campaign unrivaled until the concept of the “scary black rifle” reared its ugly head in the nineties. While it is true that criminals employed this weapon heavily through the seventies (count how many you see in the movies “Dolemite” or “Black Caesar”), it was the same things that attracted the weapon to criminals that attracted it to everyone else. For twenty years, this pocket stinger ruled the streets of Miami, Memphis, and Harlem. It was designed to be small, light and disposable. In the end, like any weapon, it has good points and bad, and the end user must ultimately make the decision for their own reasons...
This weapon only had one competitor in its class when it came out: the Colt .38 Detective special. In the sixties, the snub-nosed .38 ruled the concealed weapon scene. Small, comparatively powerful, and reliable, every cop had one on the ankle and every detective had one on the hip. When the MP-25 hit, you now had access to a weapon that could shoot seven rounds and then reload in the blink of an eye. Like all detachable magazine automatics, reloading is as simple as dropping the mag, and sliding in another. It was way faster than wrestling a speed-loader into a revolver, or worse, feeding individual rounds into the cylinder..."

title: For Sale:  CZ99, CZ999, handgun Zastava Arms Serbia, cal. 40S&W, new
postcontent:
Location: Portage Indiana. If you see this listing handgun it's available.

For sale: New in the box, CZ 99 (CZ999) handgun pistol caliber 40 S&W, Century International Arms, Zastava Arms Serbia (Yugoslavia). Price $899.
Magazine capacity 11+1 rounds (with the extended mags 15 and 20 rounds). Mags from Beretta 92 fit as well.
In original box, never fired, brand new. Comes with cleaning brush, manual, warranty, factory certificate of pressure testing and quality control.
This is the best handgun in the world (my opinion). A  40 S&W caliber is the best choice between the stopping power, number of rounds in the mag and the price. This is the caliber that is being used by US police, secret service and special units.
CZ 99 reassembles Sig Sauer P226, but in many ways is better and more improved then Sig. It's combat-proven all over the world, and it is the service weapon of choice for the police and military forces in many countries.
I had a CZ 99 in the military and police service and as my personal concealed carry weapon for many years. My experience is 100% positive. There was not one malfunction on any of these guns that I know of. They performed flawlessly under any condition and without cleaning, for months of extensive use, and accuracy was always the same.
The feeling and fit of the CZ 99 in your hands, while aiming and shooting, can be compared with the Mercedes amongst cars. And yes, I have been shooting many different guns and calibers for the past 25 years.  I own a Beretta 92 and a Sig Sauer as well, and have been shooting and comparing them side by side millions of times. My choice is always CZ 99. My hands are small to medium size, and it fits well.

In America, CZ 99 is known under different names and was imported by different companies:

CZ 99, CZ 99S, CZ 999, CZ999 Scorpion, ZDA, CZ05, Zastava Arms, Serbia Yugoslavia.
US importers: Nationwide sports, TD Arms, Century International Arms, Charles Daly ZDA, Arsenal, EAA.
License: KSN Industries Israel - Golan, Tressitu South Africa.
"CZ" is short for Crvena Zastava, translates to Red Flag, which is the old name of the factory from Kragujevac, Serbia. This Factory started making canons and firearms in 1800s. With the rich history and recognizable quality has set their reputation. Today they make many good quality firearms, handguns, hunting rifles, shotguns, military firearms, machine guns... including the famous AK 47s, which are practically indestructible and the most reliable in the whole world, same as CZ 99. We had these AKs and CZs falling from the chopper from 200 yards and, they worked like new afterwards.

The CZ 99 is a military-police service gun, or it can be a very dependable self defense and concealed carry gun. Alloy frame and polymer grips make it very light.

Parts exposed to high dynamic loads such as hammer, firing pin and unlocking insert (locking block) are made of the military ordnance steel
Hard-chromed barrel inside and out, no need for oiling, will never corrode. Barrel length 4,5", machined slide from one solid block of steel, full length slider rails.
Forged alloy frame, decocker and slide release in one, ambidextrous.
Good trigger SA and DA (single & double action), low recoil, firing pin block, easy field strip.
Barrel is made from same material used in the M-84 machine gun and is hard-chromed. In the test done in the USA in 1991 it was found that it dissipated heat very well. While this is not a concern with handguns nearly as much as it is with the machine guns, the ability to dissipate heat rapidly makes the barrel capable of lasting longer due to a shorter expansion/contraction cycle. After many Serbian and FBI tests (mud, water, sand, snow, ice, hot) firing 200,000 rounds from the single gun, there was not one malfunction, and accuracy was the same like the new one. 
It's been accepted like a service weapon for many different police stations in the US.
Not many people here know how good this gun is, because is not advertised globally and many after seeing it, think it's Sig Sauer. To add to that, Sig besides CZ 99, is the only official police service weapon today for many police stations in the US (in 40 S&W caliber only), replacing Beretta 92 and Glock. Portage police station is one of them.

Now is the smart and best time to invest in a good quality affordable hand gun like CZ 99. The time is coming soon when you will not be able to purchase it. They are not imported any more. Current owners know how good it is and will never sell it.
This one will go fast. So please no negotiations. Price is firm, $899.
This is private sale. I am not a gun store or a gun dealer. There is no background check, and according to Indiana law, the sale is simple and straightforward - exchanging cash and guns between hands. But, my moral obligation is to make sure that these guns end up in criminal- free and responsible hands. So please, if you can legally own guns you are welcome; if you cannot or have mental issues, you are not welcome, and I will refuse to sell to you.

This is a post ban Norinco NHM91 AK47, 7.62 X 39, imported by CSI Ont Calif.
It has the 21 inch barrel, Thumb hole stock, No Bayonet mount, No flash hider, Has a nut on the threads in the front of the barrel.
I have never tried to take the nut off to expose the threads.

 It came with one 5 round magazine, I bought the 30 round and the 75 round drum.

 This rifle had a factory modification which added a button under the magazine catch. That button required a detent to be milled in the magazine for the magazine to seat fully in the rifle.

This was an attempt to differentiate between a pre and post ban rifle and that the pre ban mags could not be used in the post ban rifle.

As opposed to modifying the rifle by lightly grinding off the button this rifle is stock new, as received, and unfired.

The two additional mags have the detent milled into them to be fully functional in this rifle or any other rifle with no issues.

" .30-06 Springfield
 Place of origin : United States. 
 In service: 1906–present. 
 Used by: USA and others. 
 Wars: World War I, World War II, Korean War, Vietnam War, to present.
In military service, the 30-06 was used in the bolt-action M1903 Springfield rifle, the bolt-action M1917 Enfield rifle, the semi-automatic M1 Garand, the M1941 Johnson Rifle, the Famage Mauser, the Browning Automatic Rifle (BAR), and numerous machine guns, including the M1917 and M1919 series. It served the United States in both World Wars and in the Korean War, its last major use being in Vietnam. Large volumes of surplus brass made it the basis for dozens of commercial and wildcat cartridges, as well as being extensively used for reloading. In 1908 the Model 1895 Winchester lever action rifle became the first commercially produced sporting rifle chambered in 30-06.
Ballistically, the 30-06 is one of the most versatile cartridges ever designed. With "hot" hand-loads and a rifle capable of handling them, the .30-06 is capable of performance rivaling many "magnum" cartridges. The .30-06's power (combined with the availability of surplus firearms chambered for it and demand for commercial ammunition) has kept the round as one of the most popular for hunting in North America. With appropriate loads it is suitable for any small or large heavy game found in North America.
The .30-06 cartridge was designed when shots of 1,000 yards (900 m) were expected. In 1906, the original M1906 .30-06 cartridge consisted of a 150 grains (9.7 g), flat-base cupronickel-jacketed-bullet. After WWI, the U.S. military needed better long-range performance machine guns. Based on weapons performance reports from Europe, a streamlined, 173 grains (11.2 g) boattail, gilding-metal bullet was used. The .30-06 cartridge, with the 173 grains (11.2 g) bullet was called Cartridge, .30, M1 Ball. The .30-06 cartridge was far more powerful than the smaller Japanese 6.5×50mm Arisaka cartridge and comparable to the Japanese 7.7×58mm Arisaka. The new M1 ammunition proved to be significantly more accurate than the M1906 round. In 1938, the unstained, 9.8 grams (151 gr), flat-base bullet combined with the .30-06 case became the M2 ball cartridge. The M2 Ball specifications required 2,740 feet per second (840 m/s) minimum velocity, measured 78 feet (24 m) from the muzzle. M2 Ball was the standard-issue ammunition for military rifles and machine guns until it was replaced by the 7.62×51 mm NATO round for the M14 and M60. M2 bullet was considered optimal, and many rifles performed well. The U.S. Marine Corps retained stocks of M1 ammunition for use by snipers and trained marksmen throughout the Solomon Islands campaign in the early years of the war. In an effort to increase accuracy some snipers resorted to use of the heavier .30-06 M2 armor-piercing round, a practice that would re-emerge during the Korean War. Others sought out lots of M2 ammunition produced by Denver Ordnance, which had proved to be more accurate than those produced by other wartime ammunition plants when used for sniping at long range. Commercially manufactured rifles chambered in .30-06 are popular for hunting.Current .30-06 factory ammunition varies in bullet weight from 7.1 g to 14.3 g (110 to 220 grains) in solid bullets, and as low as 3.6 g (55 grains) with the use of a sub-caliber bullet in a sabot. Loads are available with reduced velocity and pressure as well as increased velocity and pressure for stronger firearms. The .30-06 remains one of the most popular sporting cartridges in the world. Many hunting loads have over 3,000 ft-lbs of energy at the muzzle and use expanding bullets that can deliver rapid energy transfer to targets.
One reason that the 30-06 has remained entrenched as an extremely popular round for so long is that the cartridge is at the upper limit of power that is tolerable to most shooters. Recoil energy (Free recoil) greater than 20 foot pounds (27.1 joules) will cause most shooters to develop a serious flinch, and the recoil energy of an 8 pound 30-06, firing a 165 grain bullet at 2900 ft/s is 20.1 foot pounds (27.3 joules). Recoil shy shooters can opt for lighter bullets, such as a 150 grain. In the same 8 pound rifle, a 150 grain bullet at 2910 ft/s will only generate 17.6 foot pounds (23.9 joules) of recoil energy. Young shooters can start out with even lighter bullets such as the 110, 125 or 130..."

26.5 mm to .410/.45 Long Colt adapter that allows 2.5" & 3" .410 shotgun ammo or .45LC ammo to be safely fired.

Original German flap holster that is weather resistant and has room to store the pistol, cleaning brush, 26.5mm ammo, .410 or.45 ammo & one or both adapters. Holster also has a shoulder carry strap attached.

(3) 5 round boxes 2.5" .410 rifled slug ammo. (1) 25 round box of 3" - 00 buck with 5 pellets per shell, & (1) 25 round box 3"  #7.5 shot (devastating close range defense load).

title: For Sale:  LNIB SS Mini 6.8 mm SPC Ranch RARE 14,. Ruger
postcontent: To appreciate this Ruger Mini 6.8 Remington Special, you have to know something about the cartridge. I am convinced that this will probably be the round that will become the new standard issue military round for American Military Rifles. As good as the 6.5 Grendal is, this round has developed a serious following among American sportsman. The 6.8 mm Remington SPC . is a rifle cartridge that was developed by Remington Arms with collaboration from individual members of the U.S. Army Marksmanship Unit and United States Special Operations Command as a possible replacement for the 5.56 NATO cartridge in a Short Barreled Rifle/Carbine. Based upon the .30 Remington cartridge, it is midway between the 5.56×45mm NATO and 7.62×51mm NATO in bore diameter and velocity. It uses a .277 (7.036mm) diameter bullet, which is the same diameter bullet as the venerable hunting cartridge .270 Winchester uses. It is particularly adaptable to current 5.56 mm NATO firearms, the cartridge overall length being comparable. It may very well become the next standard cartridge for the U. S. military given its development in conjunction SOC and the Army Marksman Unit, as well as its increasing popularity with sportsmen. The advantages of this round are: • The 6.8mm SPC has superior terminal performance when compared to similar intermediate cartridge calibers, delivering significantly more weight down range. • Nearly 50% higher energy than 5.56mm in short-barrel AR’s. Because the cartridge length of the 6.8mm SPC is the same as the 5.56mm, the weapon systems are nearly identical, yet the 6.8mm SPC’s energy delivery is nearly double. • Extensive variety of projectiles for military and law enforcement operations to meet a variety of needs. • 6.8mm SPC can be used for hunting popular game, where 5.56mm cannot. • Available Jacketed Frangible projectiles avoid over-penetration. • Several 6.8mm SPC rounds meet barrier blind standards for FBI. • 6.8mm SPC OTM round has excellent fragmentation that meets US military requirements. No longer made, this rifle was manufactured in Southport, Conn. USA by Ruger in 6.8 REM Special. Like the Mini 14, it is a Semi-automatic Rifle with a Barrel Length of 18" The Length of Pull is 13 1/8" Stock is a black synthetic while the barrel finish is Matte Stainless Steel.
